MORE than 1 340 suspects were arrested in Gauteng over the Christmas weekend. Captain Kay Makhubele said 100 people were bust at roadblocks for driving under the influence. Police, Metro cops and Home Affairs staff worked together on the operations. “The operations commenced with roadblocks around the province, and more than 200 illegal immigrants were apprehended,” he said. “Police closed down a popular liquor outlet in Sandton, which had previously been raided during a visit by Police Minister Bheki Cele and was found to be operating illegally.” Liquor outlets in Tembisa and Kagiso were also closed down. He said police found a shebeen packed with patrons not wearing masks and not observing social distancing. “This shebeen was also operating way after curfew. The owners were arrested and the liquor was confiscated after it was discovered the outlets had no valid licences.” In Tshwane, cops arrested 450 suspects during operations to trace wanted suspects. “The suspects were arrested for murder and rape,” he said. In the West Rand, cops arrested 268 suspects for kidnapping, assault, theft, fraud and rape. In Ekurhuleni, 300 suspects were arrested for various offences. “The arrests were effected at operations that included stop and searches, patrols and roadblocks. Police arrested 20 suspects for possession of drugs, 16 for selling liquor without a licence and others for numerous serious and violent crimes,” said Makhubele. In Sedibeng, 90 suspects were arrested for crimes including house robbery, possession of stolen goods, possession of stolen vehicles, theft, drunk driving, domestic violence, malicious damage to property and selling liquor without a licence.